NAME - ::<namespace>:: emulation_dhcp_server_config

DESCRIPTION

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT, IxNetwork-NGPF

This procedure will configure DHCP Server on an Ixia port.

SYNOPSIS - ::<namespace>::emulation_dhcp_server_config

List arguments in the alphabetical order or in the reverse alphabetical order.

-encapsulation

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The encapsulation for this port. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork. Valid for functional_specification: v4_compatible, v4_v6_compatible. ETHERNET_IISAP - not supportedSNAP - LLC Routed AAL5 Snapethernet_ii - Ethernet II (default for Ethernet cards)ethernet_ii_vlan - Ethernet II with a single vlan tagethernet_ii_qinq - Inner vlan capability vc_mux_ipv4_routed - VC Mux IPv4 Routedvc_mux_fcs - VC Mux Bridged Ethernet (FCS)vc_mux - VC Mux Bridged Ethernet (no FCS)vc_mux_ipv6_routed - VC Mux IPv6 Routedllcsnap_routed - LLC Routed AAL5 Snapllcsnap_fcs - LLC Bridged Ethernet (FCS)llcsnap - LLC Bridged Ethernet (no FCS) (default for ATM cards)llcsnap_ppp - LLC Encap PPPvc_mux_ppp - VC Mux PPP

DEFAULT

 None

-handle

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

The DHCP Server handle for which the configuration will be made. Valid for -mode modify and reset. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork. Valid for functional_specification: v4_compatible, v4_v6_compatible.

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

The DHCP Server handle for which the configuration will be made. Valid for -mode modify and reset. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork. Valid for functional_specification: v4_compatible, v4_v6_compatible. When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology.

DEFAULT

 None

NOTES

IxNetwork-NGPF

When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology. If the current session or command was run with -return_detailed_handles 0 the following keys will be omitted from the command response: handle

NOTES

IxNetwork-NGPF

When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology. If the current session or command was run with -return_detailed_handles 0 the following keys will be omitted from the command response: handle

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

The DHCP Server handle for which the configuration will be made. Valid for -mode modify and reset. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork. Valid for functional_specification: v4_compatible, v4_v6_compatible. When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology.

DEFAULT

 None

local_mtu

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

Maximum Transmission Unit (MTU) is the largest packet that a given network medium can carry. Ethernet, for example, has a fixed MTU of 1500 bytes, ATM has a fixed MTU of 48 bytes, and PPP has a negotiated MTU that is usually between 500 and 2000 bytes. The parameter defines the MTU value for the Access Node. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork. Valid for functional_specification: v4_compatible, v4_v6_compatible.

DEFAULT

1500

ping_check

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

When enabled, the DHCP server issues ICMP echo requests (pings) to check for the existence of IP addresses in the network. The DHCP will not assign an IP address to a node that responds to the ICMP echo requests within the time period specified by Ping Timeout. Note that using this option will diminish the performance of the test. This option is disabled by default. This parameter is supported using the following APIs: IxTclNetwork. This is a global setting, valid for all servers. Valid for functional_specification: v4_compatible, v4_v6_compatible.

DEFAULT

0

NOTES

IxNetwork-NGPF

When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology. If the current session or command was run with -return_detailed_handles 0 the following keys will be omitted from the command response: handle
